{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778618304,"nonce":"h+yOMtmC30Y1XqG3HOqTfTSr3wo=","title":"Go-cue timing stratification for pre-go anticipation","message":"## Problem\nRecent forward-velocity diagnostics show that pre-go anticipation may be locked to absolute time since target onset rather than to the go cue. Go-cue-aligned trial-level bands suggest pre-go variability grows as aligned time approaches the go cue, but the current figures do not directly test whether this comes from early-vs-late go-cue timing.\n\n## Context\nThis should extend the existing anti-anticipation analysis rather than change training code. It is related to `5acdaae` and the `3702f54` / `f47abb1` velocity-profile results. A temporary diagnostic reloaded the relevant saved models, re-evaluated zero-perturbation trials, and compared replicate-mean variance to replicate-trial variance; the next step is a more targeted analysis of go-cue arrival time and anticipation onset.\n\n## Proposed analysis\n- Median-split or quantile-split trials by go-cue index and plot go-aligned forward velocity / position for early vs late go cues.\n- Also plot the same trials in absolute time since target onset to test whether anticipation onset is shared across go-cue conditions.\n- Estimate anticipation onset time per trial or per replicate-trial using a threshold on forward position or velocity, then regress onset against go-cue index.\n- Report whether the widening pre-go band is explained by absolute-time anticipation plus uniform go-cue timing, and whether `nn_output_pre_go=1` removes that structure.\n\n## Priority\nImportant: this affects interpretation of the anti-anticipation training results and whether pre-go penalties are solving the intended problem.\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Codex (GPT-5) \u003ccodex@openai.com\u003e","files":null}]}